  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: fbeb6d65be27d3b40a131a1e4ace56b5, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  steps:
  - message: "Wait\u2014loose crates are colliding now!"
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Thats impulse, written symbolically as J, is what we call force in time.
      It is usually associated with momentum because they share the same relationship
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 1
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "So either strong force briefly or weaker force longer\u2014both change
      momentum."
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 1
    endTime: 2
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "Exactly. Impulse links to momentum change: J = \u2206p."
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: What is specific impulse?
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Specific Impulse is the measurement used in determining the efficacy
      of rocket propellants.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 3
    endTime: 4
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Okay, then what about collisions?
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 4
    endTime: 5
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Is best define as the brief, simultaneous interaction between two or
      more bodies which is due to the internal force acting between bodies.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 6
    endTime: 7
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: 'There are two main types of collisions: Elastic and Inelastic.'
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 7
    endTime: 8
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Elastic Collision Is defined as a type of collision where the concerned
      bodies, converse both energy and momentum upon contact with each other.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 9
    endTime: 10
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "These can be Head-on or Non\u2013Head-on."
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 10
    endTime: 11
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "What\u2019s a Head-on Collision?"
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 0
    startTime: 0
    endTime: 0
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Is the type of elastic collision where the projectile is moving directly
      along a straight line.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 12
    endTime: 13
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "And a Non\u2013Head-on Collision?"
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 13
    endTime: 14
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Is the type of collision where the projectile hits the target at a certain
      angle, which resulting angle after impact is dependent on the masses of the
      object in collision.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 15
    endTime: 16
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: I see. What about Inelastic Collisions?
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 16
    endTime: 17
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: In an Inelastic Collision, target does not bend to the force generated
      by the incoming projectile, the target will move alongside the moving object.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 18
    endTime: 19
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "And what\u2019s this thing called COR?"
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 19
    endTime: 20
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: Coefficient of Restitution shows how bouncy a collision is.
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 6a96359884e70134880e3323cd90c5eb, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 21
    endTime: 22
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
  - message: "Thanks for the information, Gizmo. I\u2019ll prepare now for the quiz!"
    character: {fileID: 11400000, guid: a80ac0751277f424ca977c804190eff8, type: 2}
    dontUseTTS: 0
    useAnimation: 1
    startTime: 22
    endTime: 23
    dialogueCondition: {fileID: 0}
